                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d60">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">310/9–1250: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Austin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret   priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-09-12T16:44:00-04:00"
                            >September 12, 1950—4:44 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>508. Jebb told Gross he invited Malik to lunch today to discuss <gloss
                        target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> problem. Jebb said he “explained technical
                    aspects of question to Malik.” Latter was non-committal, saying it was a matter
                    he would have to discuss with Vishinsky<note n="1" xml:id="d60fn1">Andrei Y.
                        Vyshinsky, Soviet Minister of Foreign Affairs, Chairman of the Delegation of
                        the Soviet Union to the fifth session of the General Assembly.</note> when
                    latter arrives. Malik expressed no tentative views himself. Jebb anxious it be
                    kept secret he had invited Malik to lunch.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
